adopted, mixed race parents,
having some friends in the

00:10:30.770 --> 00:10:34.190
LGBT community who have been
impacted by this, as well--

00:10:34.190 --> 00:10:37.030
it, just, became important for
me to talk about this.

00:10:37.030 --> 00:10:39.270
I think the first time I
mentioned the idea of marriage

00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:42.440
equality was in a locker room
in an interview in 2007.

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:44.120
The interviewer looked at me
like I was crazy, like what

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:46.750
the hell is he talking about,
what's marriage equality.

00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:48.670
And someone said, oh,
that's gay marriage.

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:50.010
And I said, I don't, even, like
the idea of calling it

00:10:50.010 --> 00:10:51.330
gay marriage, to tell
you the truth.

00:10:51.330 --> 00:10:52.730
I mean, I don't call
my marriage to my

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:54.230
wife straight marriage.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:56.880
It's just marriage,
and words matter.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:58.390
Language matters.

00:10:58.390 --> 00:11:01.520
And when I was at the GLAAD
awards down in Los Angeles in

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:04.690
2009, at the table I was at,
there was a young lady there.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:08.390
And she pulls me aside, at one
point with my wife, and shares

00:11:08.390 --> 00:11:11.400
a story with me about her
younger brother who had come

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:14.860
out, at one point, as gay to
his unsuspecting, very

00:11:14.860 --> 00:11:16.010
unsupportive father.

00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:17.920
And the father really,
just, wrote him off.

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:21.160
And her brother ended up
taking his own life.

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:23.910
And she said that her father was
sort of a man's man-- you

00:11:23.910 --> 00:11:26.850
know, whatever that means, a big
football guy-- you know,

00:11:26.850 --> 00:11:28.640
really looked up to
me as a player.

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:30.950
And when he heard me talking
about the issue of marriage

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:34.960
equality and gays, in general,
it started to force him to

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:36.650
reconsider his feelings
about it.

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:37.540
So she challenged me.

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:41.650
She said, it takes people like
you for people like my dad to

00:11:41.650 --> 00:11:43.520
be able to open their
mind a little bit.

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:45.280
So she said, please keep
talking about this.

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:47.940
And I'm just honored to stand
up, be up here with these guys

00:11:47.940 --> 00:11:51.130
in a growing community and to
have watched the conversation

00:11:51.130 --> 00:11:52.640
evolve the way it has.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:55.720
Just since 2007, when I first
uttered "marriage equality,"

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:57.200
no one knew what that meant.

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:58.850
And now it's, finally,
on people's radar.

00:11:58.850 --> 00:11:59.890
People are talking about it.

00:11:59.890 --> 00:12:01.380
The conversation has evolved.

00:12:01.380 --> 00:12:03.400
And it's to the point now,
where, hopefully, we have a

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:05.370
landmark hearing, here, in a
little bit, and the decision

00:12:05.370 --> 00:12:07.460
comes through that grants
equality for everybody.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:08.480
That's what we're
all here for.

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:10.374
That's what we're all
fighting for.

00:12:10.374 --> 00:12:16.278
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:16.278 --> 00:12:18.080
FEMALE SPEAKER: I have another
question for all of you.

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:20.230
Why don't we start with
Brendon, this time.

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:25.870
What's been your experience with
homophobia in the NFL?

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:28.160
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: It's been
evolving, and that's a

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:28.870
beautiful thing.

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:30.550
So early on--

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.050
I'd say silence is consent--

00:12:36.050 --> 00:12:38.430
and so when you hear these
words, these slurs being

00:12:38.430 --> 00:12:39.980
thrown around, I would, always,
say, hey, you know you

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:41.430
can't say that.

00:12:41.430 --> 00:12:42.750
You don't need to
say "no homo."

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:44.970
You don't need to say
the f word, or

00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:49.220
replace dumb with gay.

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:52.950
So after years and years of
ingraining this into guys'

00:12:52.950 --> 00:12:56.460
heads, I went from 20 times a
day, and then after a couple

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:58.570
of years, you know, it
was 19.5 times a day.

00:12:58.570 --> 00:13:01.080
So I was keeping metrics.

00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:02.070
FEMALE SPEAKER: We like
that in people.

00:13:02.070 --> 00:13:03.790
BRENDON AYANBADEJO:
Yeah, it wasn't

00:13:03.790 --> 00:13:07.400
working, but it was working.

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:12.000
It's come full circle to, you
know, not really knowing of

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.400
any allies, not really knowing
that, publicly, that he

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:18.490
supported LGBT rights to, you
know, Kluwe stepping up, to

00:13:18.490 --> 00:13:19.680
other players stepping up.

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:23.590
And now we have this
t-shirt, now.

00:13:23.590 --> 00:13:29.330
And so this t-shirt, here, the
NFLPA endorsed this shirt.

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:31.290
So DeMaurice Smith, our
Executive Director, he

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:33.350
supports LGBT rights,
and so does our

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:35.690
President, Domonique Foxworth.

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:38.890
So I approached them with an
idea, one day, that we need to

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:42.110
come up with some type of
endorsement for LGBT rights.

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:45.880
And it was something as simple
as a t-shirt, and the proceeds

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:48.700
will go towards LGBT
advocacy groups.

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:52.100
And that's how far we've come--
from people calling me

00:13:52.100 --> 00:13:55.810
the three-letter f word to,
now, everybody starting to

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:57.020
build this critical mass.

00:13:57.020 --> 00:14:00.460
And they're starting to see
that everybody deserves

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:02.300
equality, but I think the most
important thing is we are

00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:03.670
having the conversation.

00:14:03.670 --> 00:14:06.680
And even if guys don't support
it, we're having the

00:14:06.680 --> 00:14:07.630
conversation.

00:14:07.630 --> 00:14:10.550
And guys are learning things
and they're hearing things

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:14.890
that they never heard before--
from people being born gay--

00:14:14.890 --> 00:14:16.750
they've never heard that
before-- to being

00:14:16.750 --> 00:14:17.980
gay is not a sin.

00:14:17.980 --> 00:14:21.310
And you know, you've been taught
this, basically, since

00:14:21.310 --> 00:14:23.950
the day you came out via
religion and other things in

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:27.580
ignorance, that being gay is
perfectly normal, and God

00:14:27.580 --> 00:14:28.740
created you that way.

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.730
We're having the conversation,
and that's where we've come.

00:14:30.730 --> 00:14:32.240
SCOTT FUJITA: Yeah, I'm so glad
Brendon mentioned the

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:32.765
idea for these t-shirts.

00:14:32.765 --> 00:14:34.310
I mean, it's a great
idea by him.

00:14:34.310 --> 00:14:36.150
I sit on the executive committee
as a Vice President

00:14:36.150 --> 00:14:37.200
for our players' union.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:39.400
I've been on the board,
now, for four years.

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:41.580
You know, as me, I'm always
viewed as the, sort of,

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:43.850
gay-loving, tree-hugging
socialist from Berkeley.

00:14:43.850 --> 00:14:46.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:48.560
SCOTT FUJITA: I like the idea
of the union getting behind

00:14:48.560 --> 00:14:50.490
more social progressive issues,
but I was, also,

00:14:50.490 --> 00:14:52.560
elected to be in this position
where you have to take

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:54.120
everybody's feelings
into consideration.

00:14:54.120 --> 00:14:58.030
And advancing ideas like that--
you know, good for the

00:14:58.030 --> 00:14:59.080
broader membership--

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:00.890
so to have someone like Brendon,
who is a new player

00:15:00.890 --> 00:15:03.590
rep, come in with this great
idea and have our leadership

00:15:03.590 --> 00:15:05.670
embrace it like that,
it's huge.

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:06.140
It's huge.

00:15:06.140 --> 00:15:08.300
And again, it's not so much
about a political issue.

00:15:08.300 --> 00:15:10.410
And that's one of the things
that we, always, struggle

00:15:10.410 --> 00:15:12.950
with, trying to convey to, not
just our members in the

00:15:12.950 --> 00:15:14.680
players' union, but,
really, everybody.

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:15.770
It's not a political issue.

00:15:15.770 --> 00:15:17.150
This is a people issue.

00:15:17.150 --> 00:15:19.060
It's a people issue
about people.

00:15:19.060 --> 00:15:20.620
And that's the struggle.

00:15:20.620 --> 00:15:22.330
It's changing the conversation
so that people

00:15:22.330 --> 00:15:24.530
understand it that way.

00:15:24.530 --> 00:15:26.150
And I'm glad we're getting to
the point where we can have

00:15:26.150 --> 00:15:27.486
the conversation.

00:15:27.486 --> 00:15:29.770
CHRIS KLUWE: Yeah, and it's,
also, from what I've seen, the

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:33.470
younger players coming into the
NFL are raised more in an

00:15:33.470 --> 00:15:36.680
environment of tolerance and
respect, and that's just the

00:15:36.680 --> 00:15:38.020
world that they're
growing up in.

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:40.120
And you can, really, see that
in their attitudes, because

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:43.000
they look at this issue, and
they're like, well, who cares?

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.260
Why does anyone care
who you marry?

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:47.350
And you know, it's not all of
them, because just like

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:49.010
society, it's not everyone.

00:15:49.010 --> 00:15:51.720
But the tide is shifting, and
you're starting to see that

00:15:51.720 --> 00:15:55.080
more and more in the views of
the younger generation.

00:15:55.080 --> 00:15:57.760
And that's something that we
just have to keep working at

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:00.350
it and realize that this is
a generational issue.

00:16:00.350 --> 00:16:01.910
It's like suffrage.

00:16:01.910 --> 00:16:03.470
It's like segregation.

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:04.510
It's like slavery.

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:07.760
It's something that time
is going to change.

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:10.760
And we have to keep working at
it to keep changing it, but

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:12.310
it's also going to
take a while.

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:13.400
There are no easy fixes.

00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:16.640
And I've said it before, you,
basically, have to wait for

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:17.860
the old people to
die off, and--

00:16:17.860 --> 00:16:18.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:22.560
CHRIS KLUWE: You let the young
people take their place.

00:16:22.560 --> 00:16:24.320
That's really what fixes it.

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:28.000
So it's good to see that
happening in the NFL, that you

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.790
see those young people keep
cycling through--

00:16:29.790 --> 00:16:30.790
not the dying off part.

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:32.011
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:32.011 --> 00:16:33.200
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: Can I
make a point real quick?

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:34.900
FEMALE SPEAKER: Please do.

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:38.040
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: One thing
that we do see-- and I can't

00:16:38.040 --> 00:16:40.660
blame the guys themselves,
because the biggest role model

00:16:40.660 --> 00:16:42.070
that we do have is
the government.

00:16:42.070 --> 00:16:46.070
And if the government continues
to discriminate, and

00:16:46.070 --> 00:16:48.570
if you can still be fired in
38 states for being a part

00:16:48.570 --> 00:16:50.670
LGBT community, if you can still
be evicted from your

00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:53.640
home for being a part of LGBT
community, then you shouldn't

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:59.980
be so shocked when you find
people in our society that are

00:16:59.980 --> 00:17:03.920
bigots and that are saying some
of the things that they

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:06.300
say and that discriminate.

00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:08.079
So it's from the top down
from the bottom up.

00:17:08.079 --> 00:17:09.609
The people have to change,
and the government has

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:11.329
to change with it.

00:17:11.329 --> 00:17:13.109
CHRIS KLUWE: And those are the
things that we can work on.

00:17:13.109 --> 00:17:14.410
That's what we can change.

00:17:14.410 --> 00:17:17.410
I mean, that's the part where we
set the structure in place

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:19.900
that people know that, hey,
this is where society is

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:22.040
heading, and my behavior--

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:24.260
where I'm not tolerating
other people--

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:25.520
that's not accepted anymore.

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:27.089
That's not proper behavior

00:17:27.089 --> 00:17:28.460
SCOTT FUJITA: Yeah, I think
Brendon says it best.

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:30.390
It's about rights.

00:17:30.390 --> 00:17:33.590
If people can't wrap their heads
around the idea of gay

00:17:33.590 --> 00:17:35.310
rights or calling it
gay rights, just

00:17:35.310 --> 00:17:35.930
call it rights, then.

00:17:35.930 --> 00:17:36.535
It's that simple.

00:17:36.535 --> 00:17:39.080
And I think in this country,
it does come down to the

00:17:39.080 --> 00:17:39.650
government.

00:17:39.650 --> 00:17:42.270
We discriminate against people
for all kinds of reasons.

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.800
But with an issue like this,
you need an evidence-based

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:46.560
rationale to be able
to discriminate.

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:47.660
I haven't heard one yet.

00:17:47.660 --> 00:17:48.820
And we're still discriminating
against

00:17:48.820 --> 00:17:51.110
members of the LGBT community.

00:17:51.110 --> 00:17:51.630
It's so hard to say.

00:17:51.630 --> 00:17:51.940
It's a mouthful.

00:17:51.940 --> 00:17:52.917
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: Can we come
up with a new acronym?

00:17:52.917 --> 00:17:54.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:55.970
SCOTT FUJITA: You know, we
discriminate against people

00:17:55.970 --> 00:17:57.320
who are 16 years old.

00:17:57.320 --> 00:17:59.080
