00:25:20.800 --> 00:25:23.850
What is it about talking
about same sex

00:25:23.850 --> 00:25:25.210
marriage or LGBT rights?

00:25:25.210 --> 00:25:28.430
What does that, all of the
sudden, make a difference that

00:25:28.430 --> 00:25:29.870
you can't play football
anymore?

00:25:29.870 --> 00:25:32.490
So I think that's an idea that
we need to move away from-- is

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:36.280
that athletes, as role models,
have to be, only, about

00:25:36.280 --> 00:25:38.710
sports, because athletes are
so much more than that.

00:25:38.710 --> 00:25:40.700
I mean look at the three
of us, up here.

00:25:40.700 --> 00:25:42.340
We're not just football
players.

00:25:42.340 --> 00:25:43.880
We have so many other
interests.

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:46.840
And it, really, does a
disservice to people if you

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:49.700
slap a label on them and say
that's all you can be, whether

00:25:49.700 --> 00:25:52.360
it be you're just a football
player, or you're just gay.

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:55.540
It goes for anything
in society.

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:56.920
SCOTT FUJITA: Yeah, we're people
first, football players

00:25:56.920 --> 00:25:58.900
a very distant second.

00:25:58.900 --> 00:25:59.920
And he said it perfectly.

00:25:59.920 --> 00:26:02.630
You know, I don't want to say
that speaking out now is

00:26:02.630 --> 00:26:04.270
frowned upon so much like
it was, even three

00:26:04.270 --> 00:26:05.020
or four years ago.

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:06.780
I mean, the conversation,
again, is evolving.

00:26:06.780 --> 00:26:08.780
You've got young people coming
up, like Chris just mentioned,

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:11.820
too, who are just more open,
more tolerant, more accepting.

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:13.690
And you know, the coaches have
got to accept that, because

00:26:13.690 --> 00:26:15.560
you know, by and large, we
dictate the coaches' jobs,

00:26:15.560 --> 00:26:17.420
too, so they've got
to get on board.

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:20.950
Our successes and failures
dictate their livelihood, so.

00:26:20.950 --> 00:26:22.520
CHRIS KLUWE: And that's the
thing that drives me crazy is

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:25.740
the fact that if you think a
player being gay is going to

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:26.570
be a distraction--

00:26:26.570 --> 00:26:27.890
well yeah, there will be
some media attention

00:26:27.890 --> 00:26:28.430
for a week or two.

00:26:28.430 --> 00:26:30.620
But think how much better that
player would play if he didn't

00:26:30.620 --> 00:26:33.690
have to focus on hiding his
entire life from everyone

00:26:33.690 --> 00:26:34.480
around him.

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:35.765
You think that's not
a distraction?

00:26:35.765 --> 00:26:38.160
Are you kidding me?

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:40.800
That's the biggest distraction
you could possibly have.

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:42.190
SCOTT FUJITA: We need to get
past the point where something

00:26:42.190 --> 00:26:44.000
like that would be viewed as
a negative distraction.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.330
I mean, if you can't deal with
distractions in this business,

00:26:46.330 --> 00:26:47.540
you don't belong in
this business.

00:26:47.540 --> 00:26:49.736
I mean, you've got guys-- all
kinds of crazy issues, you

00:26:49.736 --> 00:26:53.180
know, in-house fighting and a
potential coaching change in

00:26:53.180 --> 00:26:54.430
the middle of the season--

00:26:54.430 --> 00:26:55.490
those are distractions.

00:26:55.490 --> 00:26:58.710
Someone being himself is not
a negative distraction.

00:26:58.710 --> 00:27:00.680
CHRIS KLUWE: Not at all.

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:01.630
FEMALE SPEAKER: Scott,
why don't I start

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:02.400
with you on this one.

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:04.680
Do you think that the
