00:27:04.680 --> 00:27:07.860
have gotten better about
disciplining players when they

00:27:07.860 --> 00:27:10.415
do make anti-gay slurs?

00:27:10.415 --> 00:27:12.090
SCOTT FUJITA: Um yeah,
it's complicated.

00:27:12.090 --> 00:27:13.400
In the NFL, I don't know
if we have disciplined

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:14.836
anybody yet for that.

00:27:14.836 --> 00:27:16.600
And I'm sort of torn and on
the fence about that.

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:19.440
I mean, when a player speaks
his mind, do I think they

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:20.820
should be fined a whole bunch
of money for that?

00:27:20.820 --> 00:27:23.360
I mean, they are exercising
their right to free speech.

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:24.050
I don't like it.

00:27:24.050 --> 00:27:26.530
I have no problem pulling guys
aside to talk about it.

00:27:26.530 --> 00:27:28.860
But if nothing else, the good
that comes from that is that

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:30.480
it starts another
conversation.

00:27:30.480 --> 00:27:33.240
And the media jumps on guys,
right now, immediately right

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:34.430
after they say something.

00:27:34.430 --> 00:27:35.880
And I never like
to be that guy.

00:27:35.880 --> 00:27:38.050
I prefer a more diplomatic,
behind the scenes, approach.

00:27:38.050 --> 00:27:40.240
I pull teammates aside,
talked about it.

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:43.170
I let them know why using the
word like faggot in the locker

00:27:43.170 --> 00:27:44.690
room might be offensive
to so many people.

00:27:44.690 --> 00:27:45.880
You never know if the guy
in the locker next to

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:46.660
you might be gay.

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:48.930
And he might equate that
as you saying, I

00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:50.330
hate gay people, which--

00:27:50.330 --> 00:27:52.580
I know you as a teammate,
I know you as a person--

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:53.470
you are not that way.

00:27:53.470 --> 00:27:54.550
You do not hate gay people.

00:27:54.550 --> 00:27:56.685
But again, it's just flipping
the conversation.

00:27:56.685 --> 00:27:58.820
And that could happen so fast.

00:27:58.820 --> 00:28:01.510
And a lot of people come from
a climate or a family

00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:04.360
atmosphere or all their boys
back home, who, that's such a

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:05.990
common part of their
vernacular.

00:28:05.990 --> 00:28:07.380
And they never thought
about it that way.

00:28:07.380 --> 00:28:07.665
You know what?

00:28:07.665 --> 00:28:08.210
That's right.

00:28:08.210 --> 00:28:10.810
Maybe they do think that I hate
the people when I say

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:11.430
that, and I don't.

00:28:11.430 --> 00:28:12.590
Maybe I should stop
saying that.

00:28:12.590 --> 00:28:15.190
So it's, just, flipping
the conversation.

00:28:15.190 --> 00:28:17.360
CHRIS KLUWE: Yeah, and I think
it's also about, not so much

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:18.540
punishment, it's about
awareness.

00:28:18.540 --> 00:28:21.500
It's about making guys aware of,
I've said something that

00:28:21.500 --> 00:28:24.550
can affect a whole group of
people, and I should realize

00:28:24.550 --> 00:28:26.470
why what I said is wrong.

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:29.250
And you know, like, when Chris
Culliver made his statements

00:28:29.250 --> 00:28:30.080
before the Super Bowl.

00:28:30.080 --> 00:28:32.580
That's something that you don't
want to jump down his

00:28:32.580 --> 00:28:34.610
throat and immediately
just discard him.

00:28:34.610 --> 00:28:39.170
You want to help him realize why
what he said makes so many

00:28:39.170 --> 00:28:40.780
people's lives so much worse.

00:28:40.780 --> 00:28:43.470
And I think that's, really, the
key, like what Scott said,

00:28:43.470 --> 00:28:47.250
is educating these guys and
just making them aware of

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:48.170
other people's lives.

00:28:48.170 --> 00:28:51.660
And you see that a lot in our
Congress, in Republican

00:28:51.660 --> 00:28:54.680
policymakers that, all of the
sudden, they have a family

00:28:54.680 --> 00:28:58.210
member that comes out as gay,
and their voting switches

00:28:58.210 --> 00:28:59.446
dramatically.

00:28:59.446 --> 00:29:01.790
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: He
was 25 years old.

00:29:01.790 --> 00:29:02.800
He was born that way, but--

00:29:02.800 --> 00:29:06.610
CHRIS KLUWE: Yeah right, so as
you see stuff like that.

00:29:06.610 --> 00:29:09.380
A lot of times it takes that
personal connection, and a lot

00:29:09.380 --> 00:29:10.250
of that is education.

00:29:10.250 --> 00:29:12.250
It's realizing the fact that
there are other people out in

00:29:12.250 --> 00:29:14.315
the world and learning
about that.

00:29:14.315 --> 00:29:16.120
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: I think
it is an education.

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:20.540
You bring a concept to somebody
that people are born

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:21.900
gay, and they, just--

00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:25.400
oh my god, show me the proof,
show me the evidence, no way,

00:29:25.400 --> 00:29:27.066
the Bible says--

00:29:27.066 --> 00:29:28.210
I'm, like, damn.

00:29:28.210 --> 00:29:31.420
It's like, I don't see Muslims
and Jews trying to ban bacon

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:33.700
double cheeseburgers, but you
zealots are trying to ban

00:29:33.700 --> 00:29:35.450
freakin' gay marriage,
you know.

00:29:35.450 --> 00:29:40.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:40.250 --> 00:29:42.140
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: So
