00:40:31.940 --> 00:40:32.540
coming out?

00:40:32.540 --> 00:40:33.690
Is it this month?

00:40:33.690 --> 00:40:35.600
CHRIS KLUWE: Yeah, this
month, June 25th.

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:41.450
And it kind of builds off this
idea that the struggle for gay

00:40:41.450 --> 00:40:43.500
rights is also a smaller
part of the

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:44.430
struggle for human rights.

00:40:44.430 --> 00:40:48.510
And that's something that
societies as a whole have not

00:40:48.510 --> 00:40:51.300
found a way to fix throughout
our entire history.

00:40:51.300 --> 00:40:53.450
I mean, if you look at every
single civilization throughout

00:40:53.450 --> 00:40:55.120
the span of human history,
they have all failed.

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:57.045
And it's all been due to
a lack of empathy.

00:40:57.045 --> 00:40:59.350
It's been due to a lack of being
able to put yourself in

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:02.490
someone else's shoes and
realizing that if this course

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:05.450
of action harms someone else,
then it's going to be

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:08.280
detrimental in the long run,
whether you create conflicts

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:10.890
from within, from oppressing
your own people, or if you

00:41:10.890 --> 00:41:12.990
create conflicts from without,
by trying to take something

00:41:12.990 --> 00:41:13.730
from someone else.

00:41:13.730 --> 00:41:16.590
And so that's one of the main
ideas in this book is that, as

00:41:16.590 --> 00:41:19.120
a civilization, if we want to
stand the test of time, if we

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:22.740
want to last in geological
terms, we have to figure out

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:27.110
how to preach and teach empathy
to all the members of

00:41:27.110 --> 00:41:27.760
our society.

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:29.910
And even if we can't get
everyone, we can

00:41:29.910 --> 00:41:30.700
treat it like a vaccine.

00:41:30.700 --> 00:41:33.555
If we get 90% of the people in
our society to have empathy,

00:41:33.555 --> 00:41:35.210
it acts as herd immunity.

00:41:35.210 --> 00:41:37.360
And then the people who don't
have empathy, you can limit

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:38.960
the damage that they do.

00:41:38.960 --> 00:41:43.570
And so it's this broader look
of what does it mean to be

00:41:43.570 --> 00:41:45.410
successful civilization,
and are we going to

00:41:45.410 --> 00:41:46.410
be able to do that.

00:41:46.410 --> 00:41:49.130
And then there's also a lot of
random stuff, like funny

00:41:49.130 --> 00:41:52.650
writings, short stories, my
letter to Emmett Burns.

00:41:52.650 --> 00:41:53.960
There are various
other things.

00:41:53.960 --> 00:41:57.620
And it's really, I like to
describe it as a look inside

00:41:57.620 --> 00:41:59.070
my mind, so buyer beware.

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:00.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:00.670 --> 00:42:02.880
CHRIS KLUWE: One of the
underlying foundations is this

00:42:02.880 --> 00:42:04.700
idea that we have to treat
people the right way, and it's

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:06.030
not a hard concept.

00:42:06.030 --> 00:42:08.400
It's A very easy philosophical
concept.

00:42:08.400 --> 00:42:10.430
It's treat others the way you
would like to be treated.

00:42:10.430 --> 00:42:12.270
I mean, we all learned
it in kindergarten.

00:42:12.270 --> 00:42:16.500
It's really simple, so yeah.

00:42:16.500 --> 00:42:17.950
FEMALE SPEAKER: Questions
from the audience?

00:42:17.950 --> 00:42:20.220
Susie?

00:42:20.220 --> 00:42:23.800
Are there efforts to teach the
