It puts it on their radar.

00:45:19.960 --> 00:45:21.460
Again, you can't get your
hands on everybody,

00:45:21.460 --> 00:45:23.070
as hard as we try.

00:45:23.070 --> 00:45:25.060
But it's all about flipping
the conversation.

00:45:25.060 --> 00:45:26.920
I know I keep saying that,
but it's about empathy.

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:27.960
Teach empathy.

00:45:27.960 --> 00:45:29.120
I mean, you can still
teach toughness

00:45:29.120 --> 00:45:29.830
in the game of football.

00:45:29.830 --> 00:45:32.310
This is a tough game, but you
can, also, teach empathy.

00:45:32.310 --> 00:45:34.130
There's nothing wrong
with that.

00:45:34.130 --> 00:45:36.130
CHRIS KLUWE: For me, it's
the fact that it is a

00:45:36.130 --> 00:45:37.100
generational issue.

00:45:37.100 --> 00:45:40.980
And the fact is older people,
right now, have not grown up

00:45:40.980 --> 00:45:42.590
in an environment where they've
been around gay

00:45:42.590 --> 00:45:45.880
people, openly gay people, so
to them that's going to be

00:45:45.880 --> 00:45:48.480
their natural reaction
is that--

00:45:48.480 --> 00:45:50.130
even if they're supportive,
they're going to be, like,

00:45:50.130 --> 00:45:53.120
look, do what you want to do,
but just leave me out of it.

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:53.990
I don't want to know about it.

00:45:53.990 --> 00:45:57.430
The thing is, as our kids grow
up, as the younger generations

00:45:57.430 --> 00:45:59.470
grow up, they have gay friends,
they have gay

00:45:59.470 --> 00:46:02.030
siblings, they have gay
teammates, and they

00:46:02.030 --> 00:46:02.880
know about it now.

00:46:02.880 --> 00:46:06.090
You have that education, where
that's how society will shift.

00:46:06.090 --> 00:46:07.660
And unfortunately,
like I said, it

00:46:07.660 --> 00:46:09.460
is a long term change.

00:46:09.460 --> 00:46:11.994
It's not something you can just
flip a switch and all of

00:46:11.994 --> 00:46:13.140
the sudden everyone's like--

00:46:13.140 --> 00:46:17.240
I understand now, I'm being a
dick to someone, I probably

00:46:17.240 --> 00:46:17.930
shouldn't do that.

00:46:17.930 --> 00:46:19.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:20.620
CHRIS KLUWE: It's going
to take a while.

00:46:20.620 --> 00:46:25.270
And the key is that if you think
someone is receptive

00:46:25.270 --> 00:46:28.330
enough, you can tell them, look,
you may not want to know

00:46:28.330 --> 00:46:30.300
about it, but this is part
of someone's life.

00:46:30.300 --> 00:46:33.100
This is part of my life, and I
would like you to know about

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:37.450
it, so then you can understand
where I'm coming from.

00:46:37.450 --> 00:46:41.490
BRENDON AYANBADEJO: I. Always,
say that the LGBT community

00:46:41.490 --> 00:46:44.400
is, obviously, a disenfranchised
